  "market_context": "On the previous day, price reached into the previous day's high, formed a V-shape reversal with a change in state of delivery alongside an SMT divergence, and displaced lower with a bearish daily close. This established a bearish candle 2 closure, setting up a continuation lower on the next day.",
  "key_observation": "After a bearish candle 2 closure on the daily, the analyst sought continuation on the hourly: price should open, trade higher into a point of interest (fair value gap / T-spot or EQ), confirm the wick with a change in state of delivery, then expand lower.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified the previous daily candle as a V-shape reversal at the previous day's high with CISD and SMT, closing bearish — a candle 2 closure setting a bearish bias.",
    "Step 2: Anticipated a candle 3 continuation lower, expecting price to open, trade higher first into the T-spot or EQ of the prior candle to fill a point of interest.",
    "Step 3: On the hourly, located a fair value gap as the point of interest within the T-spot zone for the short entry.",
    "Step 4: Noted price did not immediately react at the FVG — instead consolidated, swept a short-term high (liquidity grab), then printed a change in state of delivery confirming the wick high.",
    "Step 5: Since this occurred during Asia / early session, executed on the higher (hourly) time frame rather than dropping to LTF: short entry with stop above the swept high, targeting 2R (using candle body to adjust to a clean 2R).",
    "Step 6: Price expanded lower and reached the 2R target."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade reached the 2R target as price expanded lower from the fair value gap after the change in state of delivery.",
  "lessons": "For a continuation setup, wait for price to open, reach into a point of interest (FVG in the T-spot/EQ), and form a change in state of delivery confirming the higher time frame candle's wick before entering — execute on the higher time frame during Asia session rather than dropping to LTF.",
